    <title>Combined summary - MAD-HTLC</title>
    <updated>2023-06-14T02:43:02.997799+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2020-July/018023.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email thread on the Bitcoin-dev mailing list revolves around the vulnerabilities of off-chain cryptocurrency systems and proposes solutions to mitigate attacks. The MAD-HTLC argument is analyzed in detail, with various channel mechanisms being vulnerable to the attack. Proposed sidechains are also potentially vulnerable to the MAD-HTLC argument.Lightning Network protocol developers are considering adding disincentives for attackers, such as bribery proofs for failed attempts. Other HTLC-using systems could use similar disincentivizing. ZmnSCPxj proposes improvements to the HTLC model, such as making both Alice and Bob sign in the alice-hashlock branch and using SegWit signing to ensure the splitting of funds is enforced. These improvements can also be implemented with OP_CHECKTEMPLATEVERIFY.The email thread discusses the potential of introducing bribery proofs as an additional disincentive to discourage Bob from attacking in MAD-HTLC. There is a risk at around locktime, particularly with "natural" orphaned blocks and short-term chainsplits. Finally, the thread talks about how LN nodes need to have some commitment to the LN in the form of actual channels, which are valuable, potentially money-earning constructs, and costly to set up.The email acknowledges that it doesn't address issues of malicious miners or an attacker colluding with a miner, but honest miners now have an unhealthy incentive regarding HTLC success confirmation. It is emphasized that further investigation is required to fully understand the vulnerabilities of off-chain cryptocurrency systems and implement effective security measures.A major focus of the email exchanges is on the MAD-HTLC (Mutually Assured Destruction Hash Time Lock Contract) and its comparison with HTLC (Hash Time Lock Contract) in Bitcoin, which are analyzed for their potential vulnerabilities to bribery attacks. The authors of the MAD-HTLC paper propose a bribe attack on off-chain multiparticipant cryptocurrency systems, which can be mitigated using a gradual scorched-earth policy. However, the authors clarify that the MAD-HTLC argument applies not only to HTLCs but also to all current off-chain channel mechanisms, making these systems vulnerable to the attack even if HTLCs are not used.The article discusses various channel mechanisms such as Spilman, Poon-Dryja, Decker-Wattenhofer decrementing-nSequence, and Decker-Russell-Osuntokun mechanisms and how they are affected by MAD-HTLC. The email discussion highlights the importance of understanding the vulnerabilities of off-chain cryptocurrency systems and implementing robust security measures to protect against attacks. The MAD-HTLC argument applies not only to HTLCs but also to all current off-chain channel mechanisms, making these systems vulnerable to the attack even if HTLCs are not used.The email exchanges between various members of the Bitcoin community discuss potential bribery attacks in the Lightning Network and possible solutions to prevent them. The Lightning Network team considers a trade-off between an increased to_self_delay parameter and higher fees, with the latter being preferable. They predict that fees will not exceed 1%, except in cases of attack or extreme fee spikes. The team also clarifies that the MAD-HTLC argument applies to all channel mechanisms, not just HTLCs, and discusses the vulnerability of timelocked transactions to bribing attacks.Overall, the discussions highlight the complexities and potential vulnerabilities of various systems within the Bitcoin network, and the need for careful consideration and analysis when designing and implementing new solutions.</summary>
